---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/alternatives/attentive-alternative';
const title = 'Best Attentive Alternatives for Shopify in 2026';
const desc = 'Compare Attentive alternatives for Shopify by SMS scale, email depth, consent governance, ecommerce events, pricing, and operating fit.';
const tools = [
  { name: 'Klaviyo', best: 'Stores coordinating detailed email and SMS commerce behavior', price: 'Verify current contact and channel pricing', pros: 'Strong Shopify events and cross-channel segmentation', cons: 'Requires disciplined consent, frequency, and profile governance', source: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/pricing' },
  { name: 'Omnisend', best: 'SMB stores wanting faster multichannel setup', price: 'Verify current contact and channel pricing', pros: 'Accessible email, SMS, and ecommerce automation', cons: 'May be less suitable for complex enterprise operations', source: 'https://www.omnisend.com/pricing/' },
  { name: 'Postscript', best: 'Stores whose primary need is Shopify SMS', price: 'Verify current messaging pricing', pros: 'SMS-focused workflows and commerce use cases', cons: 'Email lifecycle may need a separate platform', source: 'https://postscript.io/' },
  { name: 'Brevo', best: 'Teams combining SMS with email and transactional messaging', price: 'Verify current send, contact, and channel pricing', pros: 'Broad messaging coverage', cons: 'Shopify-specific event depth needs validation', source: 'https://www.brevo.com/pricing/' },
  { name: 'Sequenzy', best: 'Teams that want email lifecycle ownership beside a specialist SMS tool', price: 'Verify current plan and integration coverage', pros: 'Focused lifecycle sequences and clear channel boundaries', cons: 'Not a drop-in SMS replacement; validate the handoff', source: 'https://sequenzy.io/' },
];
const faqs = [
  { question: 'Why look for an Attentive alternative?', answer: 'Stores may need a smaller operating model, more email depth, a lower-complexity SMS tool, different pricing, or clearer separation between SMS and email ownership.' },
  { question: 'Is Attentive only for large brands?', answer: 'Its fit depends on SMS volume, team capability, consent operations, and the value of its program—not only revenue size. Smaller teams should test whether they will use the operational depth.' },
  { question: 'What should I preserve during migration?', answer: 'Preserve opt-in source and timestamps, opt-outs, quiet hours, phone attributes, flow exclusions, campaign history, and the cross-channel collision rules.' },
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />
  <main class="container py-14 md:py-20">
    <nav class="mb-8 text-sm"><a class="link" href="/alternatives">Alternatives hub</a><span class="mx-2 text-slate-400">/</span><span class="text-slate-400">Attentive</span></nav>
    <header class="max-w-4xl"><span class="badge">Shopify SMS strategy guide</span><h1 class="hero-title mt-5">{title}</h1><p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-xl text-cyan-100">Attentive alternatives should be judged by the SMS program you can actually operate: consent, frequency, product and order events, email coordination, and incremental margin after message costs.</p><p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-slate-300">The biggest platform is not automatically the best fit. Choose based on message volume, internal ownership, and the role SMS plays in the customer journey.</p></header>
    <section class="mt-12 max-w-5xl overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-white/[0.08]"><table class="w-full text-left"><thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Best fit</th><th>Pros</th><th>Tradeoff</th></tr></thead><tbody>{tools.map((tool, i) => <tr class={i === 0 ? 'highlight-row' : ''}><td class="font-semibold text-white">{tool.name}</td><td>{tool.best}</td><td>{tool.pros}</td><td>{tool.cons}</td></tr>)}</tbody></table></section>
    <section class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
      <h2>Measure SMS as an incremental channel</h2><p>SMS attribution can look strong when it reaches customers who were already likely to purchase. Use holdouts or carefully matched cohorts where volume allows, and compare incremental orders, margin after discounts, opt-outs, complaints, and email collisions. A platform-reported revenue number is not proof of causal lift.</p><p>Before changing providers, map the message classes: cart urgency, shipping or service, replenishment, product launch, and winback. Each has a different consent, timing, and suppression requirement.</p>
      <h2>Platform notes</h2>{tools.map((tool, i) => <section><h3>{i + 1}. {tool.name}</h3><p><strong>Best for:</strong> {tool.best}. <strong>Pros:</strong> {tool.pros}. <strong>Cons:</strong> {tool.cons}. <strong>Pricing:</strong> {tool.price}. Review the <a href={tool.source} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official source</a> and include SMS volume, carrier or messaging fees, contacts, seats, and integration work.</p><table><tbody><tr><th>Consent test</th><td>Can the team prove opt-in, honor opt-out, enforce quiet hours, and preserve exclusions?</td></tr><tr><th>Incrementality test</th><td>Can the team compare message-driven outcomes with a reasonable baseline or holdout?</td></tr></tbody></table></section>)}
      <h2>Migration checklist</h2><ol><li>Export consent evidence, opt-outs, phone attributes, quiet hours, segments, templates, and live flow logic.</li><li>Map Shopify product, cart, order, subscription, and service events to the intended message classes.</li><li>Assign ownership for SMS compliance, deliverability, and cross-channel suppression.</li><li>Test cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback paths with an opt-out case.</li><li>Launch gradually and monitor incremental orders, margin, opt-outs, complaints, and channel collisions.</li></ol>
      <h2>Verdict</h2><p>Choose Klaviyo for deep email-and-SMS commerce behavior, Omnisend for accessible multichannel operations, Postscript for SMS-first Shopify work, Brevo for broad messaging, and Sequenzy when email lifecycle should sit beside a specialist SMS tool. Keep Attentive when its scale and operating depth are genuinely used; otherwise a narrower stack may be easier to govern.</p>
    </section>
    <FaqSection faqs={faqs} />
    <p class="mt-12 text-slate-300">Continue with the <a class="link" href="/apps">app profiles</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use cases</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides">operator guides</a>.</p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
